      <text xml:space="preserve">This article is about the [[demographics|demographic]] features of the [[population]] of the [[Central African Republic]], including [[population density]], [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]], education level, health of the populace, economic status, religious affiliations and other aspects of the population.

[[Image:Central African Republic-demography.png|thumb|300px|right|Demographics of Central African Republic, Data of [[FAO]], year 2005 ; Number of inhabitants in thousands.]]
There are more than 80 ethnic groups in the [[Central African Republic]] (CAR), each with its own language. About 50% are [[Baya|Baya-Mandjia]], 40% [[Banda (CAR)|Banda]] (largely located in the northern and central parts of the country), and 7% are [[M'Baka]] (southwestern corner of the CAR). [[Sangho]], the language of a small group along the [[Oubangui]] River, is the national language spoken by the majority of Central Africans. Only a small part of the population has more than an elemental knowledge of French, the official language.

More than 55% of the population of the CAR lives in rural areas. The chief agricultural areas are around the [[Bossangoa]] and [[Bambari]]. [[Bangui]], [[Berberati]], [[Bangassou]], and [[Bossangoa]] are the most densely populated urban centers.

